Upcoming Actions
    In the coming months, we expect to propose rules regarding=20
registration procedures, business conduct standards, and capital,=20
margin, segregation, and record keeping requirements for security-based=20
swap dealers and major security-based swap participants. We also expect=20
to propose joint rules with the CFTC governing the definitions of=20
``swap'' and ``security-based swap,'' as well as the regulation of=20
``mixed swaps.''
    The SEC has been carefully reviewing all the comments received=20
regarding the rules that already have been proposed and we are in the=20
process of considering those comments. We also are continuing=20
discussions with various market participants about their concerns and=20
ideas regarding the proposed rules. This information is invaluable as=20
we move toward consideration of final rules designed to further the=20
purposes of the Dodd-Frank Act and the SEC's mission to protect=20
investors, maintain fair, orderly, and efficient markets, promote the=20
prompt and accurate clearance and settlement of securities=20
transactions, and facilitate capital formation and provide effective=20
regulation of the security-based swap markets without imposing=20
unjustified costs or having unforeseen adverse consequences. We will,=20
of course, be engaged in the same process for our upcoming proposed=20
rulemakings, and I would like to take this opportunity to encourage=20
market participants and the public to continue submitting comments on=20
these upcoming proposed rulemakings.
Anticipated Completion of Rulemaking
    We are working to complete the rulemaking proposal and adoption=20
process under Titles VII and VIII and are mindful of Congress'=20
deadlines for implementation. Nonetheless, this is a very challenging=20
task. The OTC derivatives markets are large and interconnected. The=20
issues are complex and do not lend themselves to easy solutions. We are=20
progressing at a deliberate pace, taking the time necessary to=20
thoughtfully consider the issues raised by the various rulemakings=20
before proposing specific rules. We are taking a similar approach as we=20
move toward consideration of final rules. As we do so, we are also=20
