    A much discussed part of the act is the requirement that banks push=20
portions of their swap activity into affiliates or face restrictions on=20
their access to the discount window or deposit insurance. Under the=20
push-out provisions, banking organizations with deposit insurance or=20
access to the Federal Reserve's discount window will have to reorganize=20
some of their derivatives activity, pushing certain types of swaps out=20
of subsidiary banks and into distinct legal entities that will require=20
their own capitalization and separate documentation of trades with=20
existing customers. The act permits domestic banks to continue to=20
engage in derivatives activities that have been a traditional focus of=20
banks, including hedging activities and dealing in interest rate swaps,=20
currency swaps, certain cleared credit default swaps, and other swaps=20
that reference assets that banks are eligible to hold. However, because=20
of the specific language contained in the act, this exemption for=20
traditional bank derivatives activities does not apply to U.S. branches=20
of foreign banking firms that by law have access to the Federal=20
Reserve's discount window. A possibly unintended effect of the act's=20
push-out provision may be to require some foreign firms to reorganize=20
their existing U.S. derivatives activities to a greater extent than=20
U.S. firms. Proposed rules to implement this section are still under=20
development by the banking agencies.
Conclusion
    As the implementation process for the act continues, the challenge=20
facing the Board is to enhance supervision, oversight, and prudential=20
standards of major derivatives market participants in a manner that=20
promotes more-effective risk management and reduces systemic risk, yet=20
retain the significant benefits of derivatives to the businesses and=20
investors who use them to manage financial market risks. The Board is=20
working diligently to achieve these goals.
