III. Background on the OTC Rates and Credit Derivatives Marketplace
    There are generally two institutional marketplaces for over-the-
counter (OTC) credit and rates derivatives: the dealer-to-customer=20
market (institutional) and the interdealer market (wholesale). In the=20
institutional market, certain dealers act as market makers and buy and=20
sell derivatives with their institutional customers (e.g., asset=20
managers, corporations, pension funds, etc.) on a fully disclosed and=20
principal basis. In the institutional market, the provision of=20
liquidity is essential for corporations, municipalities and Government=20
organizations (i.e., end users), which have numerous different asset=20
and liability profiles to manage. The need for customized risk=20
management solutions has led to a market that relies on flexibility--so=20
end users can adequately hedge interest rate exposure--and liquidity=20
providers, who have the ability to absorb the varied risk profiles of=20
end users by trading standard and customized derivatives. These market=20
makers then often look to the wholesale market--the market wherein=20
dealers trade derivatives with one another--to obtain liquidity or=20
offset risk as a result of transactions effected in the institutional=20
market or simply to hedge the risk in their portfolios.
    In the wholesale or inter-dealer market, brokers (IDBs) act as=20
intermediaries working to facilitate transactions between dealers.=20
There is no centralized exchange (i.e., derivatives are traded over-
the-counter), and as a result, dealers look to IDBs to obtain=20
information and liquidity while at the same time preserving anonymity=20
in their trades. Currently, in the United States, these trades are=20
primarily accomplished bilaterally through voice brokering. By=20
providing a service through which the largest and most active dealers=20
can trade anonymously, IDBs prevent other dealers from discerning a=20
particular dealer's trading strategies, which in turn (i) reduces the=20
costs associated with the market knowing a particular dealer is looking=20
to buy or sell a certain quantity of derivatives, (ii) allows the=20
dealer to buy or sell derivatives in varying sizes, providing stability=20
to the marketplace, and (iii) enhances liquidity in the marketplace.
    Both the wholesale and institutional derivatives markets trade=20
primarily through bilateral voice trading, with less than 5 percent of=20
the institutional business trading electronically. In these markets,=20
trades are often booked manually into back office systems and trades=20
are confirmed manually (by fax or other writing), and some (but not=20
all) derivatives trades are cleared.
    With the implementation of the Dodd-Frank Act, we expect that most=20
of the interest rate and credit derivatives markets will be subject to=20
mandatory clearing, and therefore be traded on a regulated swap market.=20
Accordingly, with increased electronic trading, the credit and rates=20
derivatives markets will be much more transparent (with increased=20
pretrade price transparency) and efficient, and systemic risk will be=20
greatly reduced as the regulated swaps markets will have direct links=20
to designated clearing organizations (DCOs) and swap data repositories=20
(SDRs).
    In light of the foregoing and with the forthcoming business conduct=20
standards, we believe the trading mandate was not intended to be and=20
does not need to be artificially and arbitrarily prescriptive to=20
achieve the goals of the Dodd-Frank Act. Indeed, to do so, would=20
undermine these goals. For example, by mandating a minimum of five=20
liquidity providers from which a market participant can seek prices=20
would likely reduce liquidity and effectively reduce the ability for=20
end users to adequately manage their risk. In short, regulated (i) swap=20
market trading (without regard to trading model but with the=20
appropriate transparency and regulatory oversight), (ii) clearing and=20
(iii) reporting is what will accomplish the policy goals without=20
hurting liquidity and disrupting the market. It is critical that the=20
Commissions do not propose rules that artificially and unnecessarily=20
hurt the market and undermine the goals of the Dodd-Frank Act.
IV. Key Considerations for SEF Rulemaking
SEFs
    As noted above, it is imperative that the Commissions adopt rules=20
that are clear and allow for flexibility in the manner of execution for=20
market participants. This will give the market choices, confidence and=20
liquidity, and will do so in a regulated framework that promotes the=20
trading of swaps, in an efficient and transparent manner.
    Consistent with the goals of the Dodd-Frank Act, for institutional=20
users, a SEF should (i) provide pretrade price transparency through any=20
appropriate mechanism that allows for screen-based quotes that provide=20
an adequate snapshot of the market (e.g., through streaming prices for=20
standardized transactions and competitive real time quotes for larger=20
or more customized transactions), (ii) incorporate a facility through=20
which multiple participants can trade with each other (i.e., must have=20
competition among liquidity providers), (iii) have objective standards=20
for participation that maintain the structure of liquidity providers=20
(like swap dealers) providing liquidity to liquidity takers=20
(institutional buy-side clients), (iv) have the ability to adhere to=20
the core principles that are determined to be applicable to SEFs, (v)=20
provide access to a broad range of participants in the OTC derivatives=20
market, allowing such participants to have access to trades with a=20
broad range of dealers and a broad range of DCOs; (vi) allow for equal=20
and fair access to all the DCOs and allow market participants the=20
choice of DCO on a per trade basis, and (vii) have direct connectivity=20
to all the SDRs.
    In order to register and operate as a SEF, the ``trading system or=20
platform'' must comply with the enumerated Core Principles in the Dodd-
Frank Act applicable to SEFs. Regulators have the authority to=20
determine the manner in which a SEF complies with the statutory core=20
principles, and there is discretion for the Commissions to retain=20
distinct regulatory characteristics for SEFs versus DCMs. It is=20
critically important for the Commissions to apply the principles with=20
flexibility given the market structure in which swaps are traded.=20
Accordingly, regulators should interpret core principles in a way in=20
which SEF's can actually comply with them. While many of the SEF Core=20
Principles are broad, principle-based concepts--which make sense given=20
the potential for different types of SEFs and trading models--some of=20
the Core Principles are potentially problematic for SEFs that do not=20
operate a central limit order book or clearing.
Ownership and Governance
    As noted above, Tradeweb was launched by market participants, and=20
has benefited from their investment of capital, market expertise, and=20
efforts to foster the development of more transparent and efficient=20
markets. With the help of its board, comprised of market and nonmarket=20
participants, Tradeweb has since its inception brought transparency and=20
efficiency to the fixed income and derivatives marketplace.
    The success story of Tradeweb may not have been possible if overly=20
prescriptive governance and ownership limits had been imposed at the=20
time. It was highly unlikely that under those circumstances, any market=20
participants would have made an investment. Moreover, beyond the=20
initial seed capital, the banks' participation also allowed Tradeweb to=20
continue to invest in its infrastructure and evolve with the market--
thus building the robust and scalable architecture that has allowed it=20
to expand to 20 markets, survive 9/11 (Tradeweb's U.S. office was in=20
the North Tower of the World Trade Center), and develop connectivity=20
with over 2,000 institutions globally. Under the proposed rules of the=20
CFTC and the SEC, ownership and independent director limits will be=20
imposed on the different registered entities that will provide the=20
technological infrastructure to the swaps market--from trading to=20
clearing. Tradeweb believes that independent directors are a very good=20
idea, in terms of bringing an independent perspective to the governing=20
board, but their duties must be consistent with other board members.=20
However, artificial caps on ownership or excessive minimum voting=20
requirements for independent directors on the board (such as 51 percent=20
of the voting power) go too far. As a practical matter, ownership=20
limits will impair registered entities such as trading platforms and=20
clearing organizations, from raising capital, and overly expansive=20
independent director requirements will likewise hurt investment because=20
investors will lack a sufficient say in how their investment will be=20
governed. Moreover, Dodd-Frank provides other, more direct, ways in=20
which to mitigate conflicts of interest, and employing each of these=20
tools in a reasonable fashion will, in the aggregate, address the=20
potential conflicts of interest without negatively impacting investment=20
of capital and innovation in the marketplace.
    For these reasons, we urge legislators and regulators to consider a=20
more reasoned approach to mitigating conflicts of interest.
Implementation
    Because of its technological experience and expertise, Tradeweb=20
will be in a position to implement whatever trading rules are imposed=20
by the CFTC and SEC for SEFs shortly after registration. However, as we=20
note above, the implementation of Title VII of the Dodd-Frank Act will=20
require cooperation between regulators (both domestically and abroad)=20
in their rulemaking and implementation plan, as well as the cooperation=20
and investment of market participants. It is critical therefore that in=20
the first instance, the rulemaking is flexible but clear, and that each=20
facet is implementation is thought through--because a lack of=20
confidence in implementation will result in a lack of confidence in the=20
marketplace, the result of which would be a marketplace which would not=20
best serve the interests of the end user. We believe the marketplace=20
needs greater certainty in terms of how and when these regulations will=20
be implemented, and we encourage Congress and the Commissions to seek=20
public comment on these issues.
    In sum, while we support the goals of the Dodd-Frank Act and=20
believe increased regulatory oversight is good for the derivatives=20
market, we want to emphasize that flexibility in trading models for=20
execution platforms are critically important to maintain market=20
structure so end users can manage their risks in a flexible manner. If=20
you have any questions concerning our comments, please feel free to=20
contact us. We welcome the opportunity to discuss these issues further=20
