A. Lack of Consideration of Costs of Regulatory Proposals
    The Commission's rulemaking has been skewed by its failure to=20
follow the plain language of Section 15 of the Commodity Exchange Act=20
(CEA), as amended by DFA, which requires the Commission to consider the=20
costs and benefits of its action before it promulgates a regulation. In=20
addition to weighing the traditional direct costs and benefits, Section=20
15 directs the Commission to include in its evaluation of the benefits=20
of a proposed regulation the following intangibles: ``protection of=20
market participants and the public,'' ``the efficiency,=20
competitiveness, and financial integrity of futures markets,'' ``price=20
discovery,'' ``considerations of sound risk management practices,'' and=20
``other public interest considerations.'' The Commission has construed=20
this grant of permission to consider intangibles as a license to ignore=20
the real costs.
    The explicit cost-benefit analysis included in the more than 30=20
rulemakings to date and the Commission's testimony in a number of=20
congressional hearings indicate that those responsible for drafting the=20
rule proposals are operating under the mistaken interpretation that=20
Section 15(a) of the CEA excuses the Commission from performing any=20
analysis of the direct, financial costs and benefits of the proposed=20
regulation. Instead, the Commission contends that Congress permitted it=20
to justify its rule making based entirely on speculation about=20
unquantifiable benefits to some segment of the market. The drafters of=20
the proposed rules have consistently ignored the Commission's=20
obligation to fully analyze the costs imposed on third parties and on=20
the agency by its regulations.
    Commissioner Sommers forcefully called this failure to the=20
Commission's attention at the CFTC's February 24, 2011, Meeting on the=20
Thirteenth Series of Proposed Rulemakings under the Dodd-Frank Act.

