    We recognize that the changes instituted by DFA give the Commission=20
discretion, where necessary, to step back from this principles-based=20
regime. Congress amended the CEA to state that boards of trade ``shall=20
have reasonable discretion in establishing the manner in which they=20
comply with the core principles, unless otherwise determined by the=20
Commission by rule or regulation. See, e.g., DFA 735(b), amending=20
Section 5(d)(1)(B) of the CEA. But the language clearly assumes that=20
the principles-based regime will remain in effect except in limited=20
circumstances in which more specific rules addressing compliance with a=20
core principle are necessary. The Commission has used this change in=20
language, however, to propose specific requirements for multiple Core=20
Principles--almost all Core Principles in the case of DCMs--and=20
effectively eviscerate the principle-based regime that has fostered=20
success in CFTC-regulated entities for the past decade.
    The Commission's almost complete reversion to a prescriptive=20
regulatory approach converts its role from an oversight agency,=20
responsible for assuring self regulatory organizations comply with=20
sound principles, to a frontline decision maker that imposes its=20
business judgments on the operational aspects of derivatives trading=20
and clearing. This reinstitution of rule-based regulation will require=20
a substantial increase in the Commission's staff and budget and impose=20
indeterminable costs on the industry and the end users of derivatives.=20
Yet there is no evidence that this will be beneficial to the public or=20
to the functioning of the markets. In keeping with the President's=20
Executive Order to reduce unnecessary regulatory cost, the CFTC should=20
be required to reconsider each of its proposals with the goal of=20
performing those functions that are mandated by DFA.
    Further, the principles-based regime of the CFMA has facilitated=20
tremendous innovation and allowed U.S. exchanges to compete effectively=20
on a global playing field. Principles-based regulation of futures=20
exchanges and clearinghouses permitted U.S. exchanges to regain their=20
competitive position in the global market. Without unnecessary, costly=20
and burdensome regulatory review, U.S. futures exchanges have been able=20
to keep pace with rapidly changing technology and market needs by=20
introducing new products, new processes and new methods by certifying=20
compliance with the CEA. Indeed, U.S. futures exchanges have operated=20
