(b) Proposed Comparable Fee Structures under Core Principle 2 for DCMs
    In the case of certain proposed fee restrictions to be placed on=20
DCMs, the Commission not only retreats needlessly from principles-based=20
regulation but also greatly exceeds its authority under DFA. DCM Core=20
Principle 2, which appears in DFA Section 735, states, in part, that a=20
DCM ``shall establish, monitor, and enforce compliance with rules of=20
the contract market including . . . access requirements.'' Under this=20
Core Principle, the Commission has proposed rule 38.151, which states=20
that a DCM ``must provide its members, market participants and=20
independent software vendors with impartial access to its market and=20
services including . . . comparable fee structures for members, market=20
participants and independent software vendors receiving equal access=20
to, or services from, the [DCM].''
    The CFTC's attempt to regulate DCM member, market participant and=20
independent software vendor fees is unsupportable. The CFTC is=20
expressly authorized by statute to charge reasonable fees to recoup the=20
costs of services it provides. 7 U.S.C. 16a(c). The Commission may not=20
bootstrap that authority to set or limit the fees charged by DCMs or to=20
impose an industry-wide fee cap that has the effect of a tax. See=20
Federal Power Commission v. New England Power Co., 415 U.S. 345, 349=20
(1974) (``[W]hole industries are not in the category of those who may=20
be assessed [regulatory service fees], the thrust of the Act reaching=20
only specific charges for specific services to specific individuals or=20
companies.''). In any event, the CFTC's overreaching is not supported=20
by DFA. Nowhere in the CEA is the CFTC authorized to set or limit fees=20
a DCM may charge. To the extent the CFTC believes its authority to=20
oversee impartial access to trading platforms may provide a basis for=20
its assertion of authority, that attempt to read new and significant=20
powers into the CEA should be rejected.
