Requirements Regarding the Mitigation of Conflicts of Interest
    Sections 726(a) and 765 of the Dodd-Frank Act empower the CFTC and=20
SEC to adopt rules mitigating conflicts of interest with respect to any=20
DCO or Clearing Agency that clears swaps or security-based swaps. These=20
rules may include numerical limits on the control of, or the voting=20
rights with respect to, such a DCO or Clearing Agency by a specified=20
market participant (Enumerated Entity).
    LCH.Clearnet has long recognized that there are potential conflicts=20
of interest in clearinghouses. Although LCH.Clearnet's substantial OTC=20
derivatives clearing book plainly evidences the contrary, it is=20
entirely possible that clearinghouse shareholders who deal in OTC=20
derivatives may have an interest in seeing that the clearinghouse does=20
not clear the instruments in which they deal. Equally, exchanges may=20
have an interest in ensuring that a clearinghouse in which they are=20
shareholders does not clear instruments traded on competing exchanges,=20
execution facilities or in the OTC market. End users shareholders may=20
meanwhile have an interest in ensuring that a clearinghouse keeps=20
margin requirements and other associated costs artificially low.
    In recognition of the potential conflicts, LCH.Clearnet's corporate=20
charter prohibits any individual shareholder from exercising votes=20
representing more than five percent of the shares in issue, even if a=20
shareholder actually holds a number of shares amounting to more than 5=20
percent of the total number of shares in issue. This measure has=20
effectively ensured that neither a single shareholder nor a small group=20
of shareholders--whatever their origin or collective interests--has=20
been able to dominate management of LCH.Clearnet's clearinghouses and=20
determine their policies, such as which asset classes will be cleared.
    At the same time, the direct involvement of market participants in=20
our clearinghouses has facilitated innovation. Their expertise has=20
directly contributed to our ability to develop complex and technically=20
challenging services such as those we offer to the OTC marketplace. For=20
this reason, we would caution that any regulation that limits the=20
aggregate involvement of Enumerated Entities in clearinghouses might=20
risk limiting innovation in OTC clearing, as well as stifling=20
competition and increasing the cost of business in the U.S.
    During passage of the Dodd-Frank Act, Congress correctly rejected=20
the imposition of aggregate ownership and voting caps on=20
clearinghouses. We have therefore been concerned to see proposals=20
emerge from the Agencies \4\ that would re-introduce such caps. Any=20
