A.2. The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection=20
Act requires Swap Data Repositories (SDRs) and Security-Based=20
Swap Data Repositories (SB-SDRs), upon request, and after=20
notifying its primary regulator, to make data available to=20
certain other domestic and foreign regulators. The Act further=20
requires regulators requesting data to execute a written=20
confidentiality and indemnification agreement with the SDR or=20
SB-SDR prior to receiving any data. The CFTC and the SEC have=20
proposed rules for SDRs and SB-SDRs, respectively, that require=20
such confidentiality and indemnification agreements (see 75 FR=20
80808 [December 23, 2010] and 75 FR 77306 [December 10, 2010],=20
respectively). Both agencies acknowledge in their proposed=20
rules that certain domestic and foreign regulators may have=20
difficulty--or even be legally prohibited--from agreeing to=20
indemnify third parties and that the indemnification provision=20
could ``chill'' requests for information or otherwise inhibit=20
certain regulators from fulfilling their mandates. Both=20
agencies have requested comment on the required confidentiality=20
and indemnification agreements and are evaluating feedback.

Q.3. Secretary Geithner made the case before the Senate=20
Committee on Agriculture in December of 2009 that foreign=20
exchange swaps should not be treated the same as all other=20
swaps. He explained that foreign exchange markets are different=20
than other derivatives markets and already are subject to an=20
elaborate regulatory framework. He cautioned, ``These markets=20
have actually worked quite well . . . we have got a basic=20
obligation to do no harm, to make sure as we reform we do not=20
make things worse, and our judgment is that because of the=20
protections that already exist in these foreign exchange=20
markets and because they are different from derivatives, have=20
different risks, require different solutions, we will have to=20
have a slightly different approach.'' Please elaborate on=20
Secretary Geithner's statement and the importance of regulating=20
foreign exchange swaps in a manner that takes into account=20
their unique characteristics and their existing regulatory=20
framework.

A.3. Treasury issued a Notice of Proposed Determination (copy=20
enclosed) that was published in the Federal Register on May 5,=20
2011, to exempt foreign exchange swaps and forwards from the=20
Commodity Exchange Act's (CEA) definition of swap. The reasons=20
for the proposed determination are explained in the Notice.

Q.4. One of the concerns that the Investment Company Institute=20
raised about the CFTC's proposed amendments to Rule 4.5 is that=20
not knowing whether foreign exchange swaps and forwards will be=20
included in the definition of ``swap'' affects their ability to=20
analyze the effects that the changes to Rule 4.5 will have.=20
Have you discussed this issue with the CFTC? More generally,=20
are you concerned that Treasury's failure to act with respect=20
to foreign exchange swaps and forwards impedes the ability of=20
market participants to determine whether and how to comment on=20
rules and to plan for compliance with Dodd-Frank?

A.4. As noted, Treasury issued a Notice of Proposed=20
Determination on May 5, 2011 to exempt foreign exchange swaps=20
and forwards from the definition of a swap under the CEA.

Q.5. At the hearing, I asked you whether Treasury would be=20
conducting any studies with respect to the effects of=20
derivatives regulation on job creation. Your answer was=20
unclear. Please clarify your answer.

A.5. Treasury has not conducted any such studies and is not in=20
the process of conducting any study on the effects of=20
derivatives regulation on job creation.
