           OPENING STATEMENT OF CHAIRMAN TIM JOHNSON

    Chairman Johnson. I would like to call this hearing to=20
order. Due to the length of this afternoon's hearing, we will=20
limit opening statements today to myself and Ranking Member=20
Shelby, and I would ask the other Members of the Committee to=20
please submit their opening statements for the record.
    Today we will review the implementation of the new=20
regulatory framework for the OTC derivatives market required by=20
the Dodd-Frank Act. This is our Committee's first oversight=20
hearing on this issue since the passage of Dodd-Frank. While I=20
know there are many other issues that Senators may like to=20
raise with the regulators before us today, we should focus our=20
questions on the subject of this hearing.
    The Dodd-Frank Act brings needed transparency and=20
accountability to our derivatives market and addresses problems=20
that greatly exacerbated the 2008 financial crisis. I commend=20
all of the regulators here today and their staffs for their=20
extraordinary work and long hours they have dedicated to these=20
important reforms.
    Putting in a new framework to regulate the vast $600=20
trillion swaps market in this age of instantaneous global=20
capital movement is an enormously complicated task that demands=20
close cooperation with international regulators. We must create=20
new rules of the road to ensure that our financial markets=20
remain the envy of the world. Our regulators should follow=20
congressional intent to craft rules that are based on relevant=20
data that reflect the unique structure of the swaps market=20
while avoiding rulemaking for political expediency, and ask=20
Chairman Gensler and Chairman Schapiro and all our regulators=20
to work carefully to do what is necessary to get this right.
    This effort will require strong coordination both within=20
and among regulators to review the full set of final rules in a=20
holistic way before they are finalized. The regulators must=20
also integrate meaningful public input into this review. I urge=20
our regulators to work together to craft a streamlined,=20
harmonized set of workable rules that protect the ability to=20
hedge risks in a cost-effective manner and minimize unintended=20
consequences that could send American jobs overseas.
    With that, I turn to Senator Shelby.

             STATEMENT OF SENATOR RICHARD C. SHELBY

    Senator Shelby. Thank you, Mr. Chairman.
    Today the Committee will examine the implementation of the=20
Dodd-Frank Act's new derivatives regulatory scheme. There is=20
particular need for oversight in this area because Dodd-Frank=20
has needlessly, I believe, created widespread uncertainty about=20
the regulation of derivatives and threatens to impose huge=20
costs on Main Street businesses as well as on our overall=20
economy.
    The irony is that the proponents of Dodd-Frank told us that=20
the new law would bring certainty to the market and stimulate=20
economic growth. Instead, Dodd-Frank has set in motion a=20
massive regulatory rulemaking process that is on an unrealistic=20
timetable. Predictably, the result has been regulatory=20
confusion and market uncertainty.
    Regulators are hastily proposing rules to meet the=20
extremely short deadlines without fully considering either=20
their economic impact or how they interact with the rules=20
proposed by other regulators. Meanwhile, market participants=20
are scrambling to understand how the numerous and complicated=20
rules will impact their businesses. In fact, they have filed=20
thousands of comments on the proposed rules.
    The comments reveal the gravity of their concerns as well=20
as their confusion about how the rules will work in practice.=20
This process is a direct result of the poorly conceived=20
regulatory structure created by the Dodd-Frank legislation.=20
Although numerous studies have recommended consolidating our=20
financial regulators, Dodd-Frank actually dispersed authority=20
for derivatives regulation. Unfortunately, the danger of having=20
multiple regulators involved is a process marked by disorder=20
and confusion.
    For example, although regulators have proposed numerous new=20
rules for derivatives, the CFTC and the SEC have still not=20
proposed rules that clarify the definition of a swap. This=20
omission alone has had serious ramifications for our markets=20
and the implementation process. After all, if regulators do not=20
know what the definition of a swap is, how can they finalize=20
their own rules governing swap dealers or major swap=20
participants since it is unclear exactly who is covered by=20
these rules? And if market participants do not know if they=20
will be classified as a swap dealer or a major swap=20
participant, how can they be expected to know when to submit=20
comments?
    This is just one example of how Dodd-Frank has created a=20
confused derivatives rulemaking process that is not proceeding=20
in a logical order and creates significant uncertainty in our=20
markets.
    The regulatory process is further hampered by the fact that=20
the Dodd-Frank Act was so poorly drafted. Here is just one=20
example, a simple example that illustrates my point.
    One of the first Dodd-Frank rules promulgated by the CFTC=20
was an interim final rule for ``reporting pre-enactment swap=20
transactions.'' The stated purpose of the rule is to reconcile=20
two conflicted Dodd-Frank provisions: Sections 723 and 729.
    The CFTC rule proposal specifically states, and I will=20
quote, ``The inconsistencies between these two reporting=20
provisions must be reconciled in order to eliminate uncertainty=20
with respect to the actual reporting requirements for pre-
enactment swaps.'' In other words, our regulators have been=20
forced to undertake additional rulemaking in an effort to=20
correct the inconsistencies and errors in the Dodd-Frank Act.=20
And although I am not sure how rules can alter statutory=20
requirements, it is clear that Dodd-Frank has some fundamental=20
flaws and should be revisited.
    Today I look forward to hearing how the regulators plan to=20
improve this broken regulatory process, particularly how they=20
will consider and incorporate comments from the public.
    Make no mistake. The unprecedented scale and scope of=20
agency rulemakings mandated by the Dodd-Frank derivatives title=20
make it impossible for regulators to engage in deliberative and=20
rational rulemaking and still meet the unrealistic deadlines=20
imposed by the act.
    I am also concerned that the regulators are not fully=20
considering the costs and benefits of the rules and the effect=20
that these rules could have on our markets and job creation in=20
the country.
    As the American economy continues to struggle, this may be=20
the most important facet of the current regulatory process. I=20
think it must not be overlooked.
    Thank you, Mr. Chairman.
    Chairman Johnson. I would like to welcome and introduce the=20
witnesses on our first panel:
    The Honorable Mary Schapiro is Chairman of the U.S.=20
Securities and Exchange Commission. Previously, she was CEO of=20
FINRA. Ms. Schapiro also served as Commissioner of the SEC from=20
1988 to 1994 and Chairman of the Commodity Futures Trading=20
Commission from 1994 to 1996.
    The Honorable Gary Gensler is Chairman of the Commodity=20
Futures Trading Commission. Mr. Gensler previously served in=20
the Treasury Department as Under Secretary of Domestic Finance=20
and Assistant Secretary of Financial Markets. He also served as=20
senior adviser to Chairman Paul Sarbanes.
    Daniel Tarullo is a member of the Federal Reserve Board of=20
Governors. Prior to his appointment to the Board, Mr. Tarullo=20
was a professor at the Georgetown University Law Center. He=20
served as Assistant Secretary of State for Economic and=20
Business Affairs as well as Deputy Assistant to the President=20
for Economic Policy and Assistant to the President for=20
