leverage, and liquidity standards for derivatives, and the Committee on=20
Payment and Settlement Systems, which is working with the International=20
Organization of Securities Commissions to update international=20
standards for systemically important clearing systems, including=20
central counterparties that clear derivatives instruments, and trade=20
repositories. Public consultation on these revised international=20
standards is currently under way.
    The goal of all of these efforts is to develop a consistent=20
international approach to the regulation and supervision of derivatives=20
products and market infrastructures as well as to the sound=20
implementation of the agreed-upon approaches. Our aim is to promote=20
both financial stability and fair competitive conditions to the fullest=20
extent possible.
Infrastructure Issues
    The Dodd-Frank Act addressed both the infrastructure of the=20
derivatives markets and the regulation and supervision of its dealers=20
and major participants. Central counterparties are given an expanded=20
role in the clearing and settling of swap and security-based swap=20
(hereafter referred to as ``swap'') transactions, and the Board=20
believes benefits can flow from this reform. Since 2005, Federal=20
Reserve staff members have worked with market participants to=20
strengthen the infrastructure for OTC derivatives, including developing=20
and broadening the use of central clearing mechanisms and trade=20
repositories. Market participants have already established central=20
counterparties that provide clearing services for some OTC interest=20
rate, energy, and credit derivatives contracts. If properly designed,=20
managed, and overseen, central counterparties offer an important tool=20
for managing counterparty credit risk, and thus they can reduce risk to=20
market participants and to the financial system. Both central=20
counterparties and trade repositories also support regulatory oversight=20
and policymaking by providing more-comprehensive data on the=20
derivatives markets. The Board is committed to continuing to work with=20
other authorities, both in the United States and abroad, to ensure that=20
a largely consistent international approach is taken to central=20
counterparties and trade repositories and that their risk-reducing=20
benefits are realized.
