    Chairman Gensler has recently disclosed his plan for the sequencing=20
of final rulemakings under DFA. He has divided the rulemakings into=20
three categories: early, middle, and late. We agree that sequencing of=20
the rules is critical to meaningful public comment and effective=20
implementation of the rules to implement DFA. Many of the rulemakings=20
required by DFA are interrelated. That is, DFA requires many=20
intertwined rulemakings with varying deadlines. Market participants,=20
including CME cannot fully understand the implications or costs of a=20
proposed rule when that proposed rule is reliant on another rule that=20
is not yet in its final form. As a result, interested parties are=20
unable to comment on the proposed rules in a meaningful way, because=20
they cannot know the full effect.
    We agree with many, but not all aspects of the Chairman's proposed=20
sequencing agenda and have recently proposed an alternative sequencing=20
agenda to the Commissioners. We recommend that in Phase 1 (early), the=20
Commission focus on rules that are necessary to bring the previously=20
unregulated swaps market into the sound regulatory framework that=20
exists for futures markets. This set of major rulemakings represents=20
the largest amount of change for the industry and cannot be=20
satisfactorily addressed in a timely manner if key elements of the=20
regulatory framework for swaps clearing are not determined until the=20
middle or late stages of the rulemaking process. Further, the=20
regulatory framework for reducing systemic risk in OTC derivatives was=20
the central focus of DFA and therefore should have the highest=20
priority.
    We suggest that Phase II (middle) deal with exchange-trading=20
requirements for swaps, including the definition of and requirements=20
for swap trading facilities, business conduct standards for swap=20
dealers and requirements for swap data repositories. While we support=20
efforts to increase transparency in swaps markets, we believe these=20
rulemakings are less critical in time priority than the clearing=20
mandate and related clearing rules that will reduce systemic risk.
    Finally, we recommend that the Commission leave those rulemakings=20
that deal with DCMs and position limits for Phase III (late). As I=20
mention throughout my testimony, the exchange-traded derivatives market=20
operated flawlessly during the financial crisis, and the proposed rules=20
affecting DCMs and position limits, which as discussed below, often=20
represent an overstepping of the Commission's authority under DFA,=20
represent incremental changes to an already robust regulatory scheme.
    With respect to the phasing in of the mandatory clearing rules for=20
swaps, some have suggested that the clearing requirement first be=20
applied to dealer-to-dealer swaps and then later applied to dealer-to-
customer swaps. CME Group strongly disagrees with this approach insofar=20
as it may limit clearing competition and customer choice and because,=20
more importantly, it will disadvantage customers who are preparing for=20
central counterparty clearing of swaps but are unable to complete their=20
preparations due to the uncertainty associated with the lack of final=20
rules. Sell-side and buy-side participants may elect to support or=20
prefer different clearing solutions depending on how they are owned and=20
operated, the membership requirements associated with each=20
clearinghouse, and the risk management and default management features=20
associated with each clearing solution. Different clearinghouses have=20
already adopted differing approaches to these features, enhancing=20
competition and the proliferation of different business models.=20
Sequencing dealer-to-dealer clearing prior to dealer-to-customer=20
clearing lacks any rational justification and simply limits the=20
availability of competing clearing models, potentially limiting=20
competition, which Congress expressly provided for in DFA.
    The theory behind phasing in dealer-to-dealer swaps first is that=20
dealers will be prepared to begin clearing swaps before buy-side=20
participants are likewise prepared. This rationale, however, is not=20
based in fact. An overwhelming number of buy-side participants are=20
already clearing or ready to clear or will be ready to clear in the=20
near future. Ten buy-side firms are already clearing at CME Group.=20
Another 30 are testing with us and have informed us that they are=20
planning to be prepared to clear no later than July 15. Another 80 buy-
side firms are in the pipeline to clear with us and would like to be=20
ready to clear voluntarily approximately 3-6 months before mandated to=20
do so. Also, UBS recently conducted a comprehensive study (March 10,=20
2011) of OTC derivatives market participants to gauge the readiness on=20
the buy-side for this transition. Their study found that buy-side firms=20
are increasingly prepared to clear OTC derivatives, reporting that 73=20
percent of firms are already clearing or preparing to clear, 71 percent=20
expect to begin clearing within 12 months, and 82 percent expect that=20
the majority of their OTC businesses will be cleared within 2 years.=20
Claims that buy-side participants are not ready to clear are simply=20
false and will disadvantage buy-side firms that wish to reduce=20
bilateral clearing risks by adopting central counterparty clearing as=20
soon as possible.
    We believe that the most efficient way to implement the clearing=20
mandate is to phase in the mandate on a product-class by product-class=20
basis. Once the CFTC defines ``class,'' it can mandate that large=20
classes of instruments, such as 10-year interest rate swaps, be cleared=20
regardless of the counterparties to the trade. This approach will (i)=20
preserve customer choice in clearing, (ii) bring the largest volume of=20
swaps into clearinghouses as soon as possible, and (iii) allocate the=20
Commission's limited resources in an efficient manner. CME Group's=20
letter to Chairman Gensler, which discusses our position on both=20
sequencing of rulemaking and sequencing of implementation of the=20
clearing mandate in greater detail, is attached for your reference as=20
Exhibit A.
    The Commission should avoid creating an unlevel playing field among=20
large swap market participants--both in terms of freedom to choose=20
among competing clearing offerings and in terms of their ability to=20
reduce bilateral credit risks in a timely fashion. Congress wisely=20
recognized that major swap participants that are not swap dealers can=20
also pose systemic risks to the marketplace; hence the Commission=20
should sequence rules applying to swap dealers and major swap=20
participants at the same time.
    This Congress can mitigate some of the problems that have plagued=20
the CFTC rulemaking process by extending the rulemaking schedule so=20
that professionals, including exchanges, clearinghouses, dealers,=20
market makers, and end users can have their views heard and so that the=20
