4. Conversion From Principles-Based to Rules-Based Regulation\8\
    Some of the CFTC's rule proposals are explained by the ambiguities=20
created during the rush to push DFA to a final vote. For example,=20
Congress preserved and expanded the scheme of principles-based=20
regulation by expanding the list of core principles and granting self=20
regulatory organizations ``reasonable discretion in establishing the=20
manner in which the [self regulatory organization] complies with the=20
core principles.'' Congress granted the Commission the authority to=20
adopt rules respecting core principles, but did not direct it to=20
eliminate the principles-based regulation, which was the foundation of=20
the CFMA. In accordance with CFMA, the CFTC set forth ``[g]uidance on,=20
and Acceptable Practices in, Compliance with Core Principles'' that=20
operated as safe harbors for compliance. This approach has proven=20
effective and efficient in terms of appropriately allocating=20
responsibilities between regulated DCMs and DCOs and the CFTC.
