inflexible regime threatens to stifle growth and innovation in U.S.=20
exchanges and thereby drive market participants overseas. This, I noted=20
earlier, will certainly impact the relevant job markets in the United=20
States.
(a) Proposed Rulemaking Under Core Principle 9 for DCMs
    A specific example of the Commission's unnecessary and problematic=20
departure from the principles-based regime is its proposed rule under=20
Core Principle 9 for DCMs--Execution of Transactions, which states that=20
a DCM ``shall provide a competitive, open and efficient market and=20
mechanism for executing transactions that protects the price discovery=20
process of trading in the centralized market'' but that ``the rules of=20
a board of trade may authorize . . . (i) transfer trades or office=20
trades; (ii) an exchange of (I) futures in connection with a cash=20
commodity transaction; (II) futures for cash commodities; or (III)=20
futures for swaps; or (iii) a futures commission merchant, acting as=20
principal or agent, to enter into or confirm the execution of a=20
contract for the purchase or sale of a commodity for future delivery if=20
that contract is reported, recorded, or cleared in accordance with the=20
rules of the contract market or [DCO].''
    Proposed Rule 38.502(a) would require that 85 percent or greater of=20
the total volume of any contract listed on a DCM be traded on the DCM's=20
centralized market, as calculated over a 12 month period. The=20
Commission asserts that this is necessary because ``the price discovery=20
function of trading in the centralized market'' must be protected. 75=20
Fed. Reg. at 80588. However, Congress gave no indication in DFA that it=20
considered setting an arbitrary limit as an appropriate means to=20
regulate under the Core Principles. Indeed, in other portions of DFA,=20
where Congress thought that a numerical limit could be necessary, it=20
stated so. For example, in Section 726 addressing rulemaking on=20
Conflicts of Interest, Congress specifically stated that rules ``may=20
include numerical limits on the control of, or the voting rights'' of=20
certain specified entities in DCOs, DCMs, or SEFs.
    The Commission justifies the 85 percent requirement only with its=20
observations as to percentages of various contracts traded on various=20
exchanges. It provides no support evidencing that the requirement will=20
provide or is necessary to provide a ``competitive, open, and efficient=20
market and mechanism for executing transactions that protects the price=20
discovery process of trading in the centralized market of the board of=20
trade,'' as is required under Core Principle 9. Further, Core Principle=20
9, as noted above, expressly permits DCMs to authorize off-exchange=20
transactions including for exchanges to related positions pursuant to=20
their rules.
    The imposition of the proposed 85 percent exchange trading=20
requirement will have extremely negative effects on the industry. It=20
would significantly deter the development of new products by exchanges=20
like CME. This is because new products generally initially gain trading=20
momentum in off-exchange transactions. Indeed, it takes years for new=20
products to reach the 85 percent exchange trading requirement proposed=20
by the Commission. For example, one suite of very popular and very=20
liquid foreign exchange products developed and offered by CME would not=20
have met the 85 percent requirement for 4 years after it was initially=20
offered. The suite of products' on-exchange trading continued to=20
increase over 10 years, and it now trades only 2 percent off exchange.=20
Under the proposed rule, CME would have had to delist this suite of=20
products. \9\
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
     \9\ More specifically, the product traded 32 percent off-exchange=20
when it was first offered in 2000, 31 percent off exchange in 2001, 25=20
percent in 2002, 20 percent in 2003, finally within the 85 percent=20
requirement at 13 percent off-exchange in 2004, 10 percent in 2005, 7=20
percent in 2006, 5 percent in 2007, 3 percent in 2008, and 2 percent in=20
2009 and 2010.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Imposition of an 85 percent exchange trading requirement would also=20
have adverse effects on market participants. If instruments that are=20
most often traded off-exchange are forced onto the centralized market,=20
customers will lose cross-margin efficiencies that they currently enjoy=20
and will be forced to post additional cash or assets as margin. For=20
example, customers who currently hold open positions on CME=20
Clearport<sup>'</sup> will be required to post a total of approximately=20
$3.9 billion in margin (at the clearing firm level, across all clearing=20
firms).
(b) Proposed Comparable Fee Structures under Core Principle 2 for DCMs
    In the case of certain proposed fee restrictions to be placed on=20
DCMs, the Commission not only retreats needlessly from principles-based=20
regulation but also greatly exceeds its authority under DFA. DCM Core=20
Principle 2, which appears in DFA Section 735, states, in part, that a=20
DCM ``shall establish, monitor, and enforce compliance with rules of=20
the contract market including . . . access requirements.'' Under this=20
Core Principle, the Commission has proposed rule 38.151, which states=20
that a DCM ``must provide its members, market participants and=20
independent software vendors with impartial access to its market and=20
services including . . . comparable fee structures for members, market=20
participants and independent software vendors receiving equal access=20
to, or services from, the [DCM].''
    The CFTC's attempt to regulate DCM member, market participant and=20
independent software vendor fees is unsupportable. The CFTC is=20
expressly authorized by statute to charge reasonable fees to recoup the=20
costs of services it provides. 7 U.S.C. 16a(c). The Commission may not=20
bootstrap that authority to set or limit the fees charged by DCMs or to=20
impose an industry-wide fee cap that has the effect of a tax. See=20
Federal Power Commission v. New England Power Co., 415 U.S. 345, 349=20
(1974) (``[W]hole industries are not in the category of those who may=20
be assessed [regulatory service fees], the thrust of the Act reaching=20
only specific charges for specific services to specific individuals or=20
companies.''). In any event, the CFTC's overreaching is not supported=20
by DFA. Nowhere in the CEA is the CFTC authorized to set or limit fees=20
a DCM may charge. To the extent the CFTC believes its authority to=20
oversee impartial access to trading platforms may provide a basis for=20
its assertion of authority, that attempt to read new and significant=20
powers into the CEA should be rejected.
