9. Effects on OTC Swap Contracts
    DFA's overhaul of the regulatory framework for swaps creates=20
uncertainty about the status and validity of existing and new swap=20
contracts. Today, under provisions enacted in 2000, swaps are excluded=20
or exempt from the CEA under Sections 2(d), 2(g), and 2(h) of the CEA.=20
These provisions allow parties to enter into swap transactions without=20
worrying about whether the swaps are illegal futures contracts under=20
CEA Section 4(a). DFA repeals those exclusions and exemptions effective=20
July 16, 2011. At this time, it is unclear what if any action the CFTC=20
plans to take or legally could take to allow both swaps entered into on=20
or before July 16, and those swaps entered into after July 16 from=20
being challenged as illegal futures contracts. To address this concern,=20
Congress and the CFTC should consider some combination of deferral of=20
the effective dates of the repeal of Sections 2(d), 2(g), and 2(h),=20
exercise of CFTC exemptive power under Section 4(c), or other=20
appropriate action. Otherwise swap markets may be hit by a wave of=20
legal uncertainty which the statutory exclusions and exemptions were=20
designed in 2000 to prevent. This uncertainty may, again, chill=20
participation in the swap market and impair the ability of market=20
participants, including hedgers, to manage their risks.
