    Minimizing jurisdictional differences in rules such as those=20
mitigating conflicts in clearinghouses will be key to keeping costs low=20
and to reducing implementation challenges. In this regard we would=20
respectfully observe that in Europe, where we have been closely=20
tracking EMIR's progress through the legislature, there have been no=20
proposals to attempt to limit clearinghouse ownership or voting rights=20
by groups of entities--either from the European Commission, the=20
European Parliament, or the European Council. Indeed, the restrictions=20
on the ownership of shares or voting interests of the type proposed by=20
the Agencies would likely be deemed contrary to the fundamental=20
freedoms set out in the primary EU Treaty (the Treaty on the=20
Functioning of the European Union, ``TFEU''), in particular, those=20
protecting the freedom of establishment and the free movement of=20
capital. \6\
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
     \6\ The provisions of the TFEU relating to free movement of=20
capital provide that ``all restrictions on the movement of capital=20
between Member States and between Member States and third countries=20
shall be prohibited.'' The EU's Supreme Court (the European Court of=20
Justice, ``ECJ'') has consistently found that, for these purposes,=20
capital movements include ``direct investment in the form of=20
participation in an undertaking by way of shareholding or the=20
acquisition of securities on the capital market . . . and . . . the=20
possibility of participating effectively in the management of a company=20
or in its control.''

    The free movement of capital and freedom of establishment are=20
fundamental tenets of the TFEU, and any exceptions to these rules would=20
needs therefore to be justified by overarching public policy=20
requirements. Moreover, the TFEU sets out that ``only the Council,=20
acting in accordance with a special legislative procedure, may=20
unanimously, and after consulting the European Parliament, adopt=20
measures which constitute a step backwards in Union law as regards the=20
liberalization of the movement of capital to or from third countries.''=20
Accordingly, such an amendment would require unanimity amongst Member=20
States.
