    Under current bilateral swaps market practice, some clients are=20
able to negotiate for individual segregation of collateral that they=20
post as margins. The collateral posted by clients that have made such=20
arrangements, although subject to other risks, is not subject to the=20
risk of the default of other market participants that have entered into=20
transactions with their swaps counterparts. These clients--many of them=20
pension funds, long-term savings institutions, Government and related=20
fiscal authorities and other real money investors--believe it is=20
inappropriate that they should be subject to an additional risk (that=20
of fellow-customers) when clearing their swaps positions.
    At the specific request of customers in Europe, LCH.Clearnet has=20
developed a client clearing model that protects nondefaulting clients=20
from the risks of defaulting clients. We believe that this client-
clearing model is closely aligned to one of the models proposed by the=20
Commission in its ANPR, Option 2, or ``Legal Segregation With=20
Commingling.''
    This model improves on the protections afforded in the bilateral=20
swaps marketplace, by enabling the clearinghouse to offer clients=20
portability of swaps margin-related collateral and market risk=20
positions in the event of a clearing member's default. It is structured=20
so as to enable the clearinghouse to identify and cover the risks=20
associated with an individual customer's portfolio as if the=20
clearinghouse were required to take on its management in isolation, as=20
could happen in the event of a member default. This construct also=20
enables the clearinghouse to monitor client profiles individually and=20
to maximize the likelihood of the transfer of such clients' risks and=20
positions in the event of their clearing member(s) defaulting.
    Having implemented the above outlined model in Europe, the Group is=20
confident that it gives rise to no further costs than the CFTC's other=20
proposed models, either at the clearinghouse or at the clearing member=20
level.
    Further, LCH.Clearnet can confirm that the implementation of this=20
clearing model has not changed the structure of resources that protect=20
the clearinghouse following a default; it has not required an increase=20
in margin collateral levels, nor has it caused the clearinghouse to=20
raise clearing member contributions to the default fund.
    LCH.Clearnet looks forward to extending its existing SwapClear=20
client clearing service to U.S. end users under the well-proven FCM=20
structure. At the same time, we believe that the important client=20
protection mechanisms outlined above and described the CFTC in its ANPR=20
under ``Option 2, Legal Segregation with Comingling'' would best=20
preserve the interests of the investors and other clients clearing=20
swaps through FCMs. The introduction of such client-level protections=20
would also, we believe, ensure closer harmonization with those=20
protections afforded in Europe.
Conclusion
    As stated at the start of this testimony, LCH.Clearnet is=20
supportive of the goals of the Dodd-Frank Act. We also believe that the=20
CFTC and SEC have approached the rulemaking process with care and=20
thoroughness, and commend the Commissioners and staff for their hard=20
work.
    We applaud the Agencies for their engagement with the industry and=20
with authorities in the EU and further afield. Nonetheless, we do=20
believe that it would be helpful to reconcile the differences between=20
the U.S. and EU proposals, particularly with regard to: mitigation of=20
conflicts of interest; risk management requirements; and the protection=20
of cleared swaps, all of which we have outlined in this testimony.
    We would respectfully urge the Committee to ensure that the final=20
rules promulgated by the Agencies are aligned as closely as possible=20
with those being finalized in the EU. Such a commonality of approach=20
should reduce the cost of business, the tendency for regulatory=20
arbitrage and the likelihood of flight of capital.
    LCH.Clearnet looks forward to fulfilling its role in support of=20
this important statutory initiative and to growing our U.S. operations=20
so that more U.S. end users can benefit from the risk mitigation=20
provided through our clearing services.
    In closing, LCH.Clearnet would like to thank the Committee for=20
inviting us to discuss the new derivatives regulatory framework. We=20
appreciate the opportunity and the Committee's interest in our=20
concerns.
