Q.4. There has been an increase in litigation against banks=20
related to foreign currency trading activities. Pension funds=20
and State attorneys general allege that certain banks executed=20
trades at one price, but charged a higher price to the funds.=20
Whistleblowers have also come forward alleging improper=20
practices related to foreign currency trading by banks. An=20
October 2009 report by Russell Investments noted that there is=20
``no regulator charged with defending the rights and interests=20
of clients when converting currency.'' What work has Treasury=20
done to monitor and investigate allegations of improper=20
practices regarding currency trading? What is the current state=20
of the regulatory framework that addresses this area? What=20
options, if any, has the Department explored for enhancing=20
transparency? What, if any, legislation might be required in=20
this area to better protect clients from improper practices in=20
this area?

A.4. The Treasury Department does not comment on pending=20
litigation and investigations.
    The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection=20
Act (DFA) further strengthens the oversight and transparency of=20
all foreign currency derivatives markets, including foreign=20
exchange swaps and forwards. It subjects participants in the=20
derivatives markets to heightened business conduct standards=20
and provides the CFTC and banking regulators with additional=20
oversight of market participants and with strong anti-evasion=20
powers to ensure that they do not structure products or take=20
other steps to evade the Commodity Exchange Act's requirements.=20
The DFA's trade reporting requirements will significantly=20
enhance the transparency and oversight of derivatives markets,=20
including for foreign currency derivatives.

Q.5. Title VII of the Dodd-Frank Act, largely overseen by the=20
SEC and CFTC, will require firms to keep additional capital for=20
over-the-counter trades, so that they will be able to pay up,=20
if the trade moves against them. At the same time, the Volcker=20
Rule, which is overseen by banking regulators, as well as the=20
SEC and CFTC, also imposes capital requirements. These=20
provisions require regulators to impose additional capital=20
charges for any proprietary trading by the nonbank financial=20
companies supervised by the board [((a)(2)) and ((f)(4))], and=20
explicitly authorizes regulators to impose additional capital=20
charges on banking entities, for even permitted activities such=20
as market-making. [((d)(3))] And, of course, the Treasury=20
Department and the banking regulators are working with their=20
international counterparts to effectively implement new Basel=20
requirements on capital. What work is the Treasury Department=20
doing, whether independently or in coordination with the=20
prudential regulators, the SEC, or CFTC, to help enhance the=20
capital requirements for trading positions, as directed by not=20
just the derivatives title, but also by the Volcker Rule?

A.5. Although the Treasury Department is not directly=20
responsible for writing the regulations to implement either the=20
derivatives provisions of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and=20
Consumer Protection Act or the Volcker Rule, we are working=20
closely with the agencies responsible for issuing the=20
regulations to implement the Volcker Rule to coordinate the=20
rulemakings so that they are as consistent and comparable as=20
possible across supervisory jurisdictions.

Q.6. Historically OTC derivatives have been taxed under the=20
conventional realization method of accounting for stock, bonds,=20
and other securities, while exchange traded funds have been=20
subject to Section 1256 of the Internal Revenue Code, which=20
generally requires that contracts within its scope be marked-
to-market on an annual basis, and provides that gains or losses=20
are considered capital gains/losses with 60 percent long-term=20
and 40 percent short term. Section 1601 of the Dodd-Frank Wall=20
Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act amended Section 1256=20
of the IRC. On December 7, 2010, the Treasury/IRS business plan=20
provided for the development of ``guidance on the application=20
of [Section] 1256 to certain derivatives contracts.'' What tax=20
issues is the Department considering with respect to=20
derivatives contracts? When does the Department expect that it=20
will issue guidance in this area? If the Secretary of the=20
Treasury exempted foreign exchange swaps and forwards from the=20
definition of ``swap'' under the Commodity Exchange Act, would=20
the definition under Section 1256 of the IRC, as amended by=20
Dodd-Frank, remain applicable?

A.6. Section 1256 of the Internal Revenue Code generally=20
requires that ``section 1256 contracts'' be marked-to-market=20
annually. A section 1256 contract is a regulated futures=20
contract, a foreign currency contract, a dealer securities=20
futures contract, or certain options listed on a qualified=20
board or exchange (QBE). Gain or loss from a foreign currency=20
contract is generally treated as ordinary income and subject to=20
tax at regular income tax rates; a regulated futures contract,=20
dealer securities futures contract, and a listed option=20
generates 60 percent long-term and 40 percent short-term=20
capital gain or loss, assuming the contract is a capital asset=20
in the hands of the taxpayer.
    In recent years, an increasing number of contracts have=20
been moving to QBEs and/or centralized clearinghouses, raising=20
the question as to whether such contracts are section 1256=20
contracts. The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer=20
Protection Act added section 1256(b)(2) to the Internal Revenue=20
Code, which generally limits the scope of section 1256 to those=20
contracts that have historically been section 1256 contracts.=20
Thus, section 1256(b)(2) specifies that over-the-counter swaps=20
and similar financial instruments are not section 1256=20
contracts. The exemption of foreign exchange swaps and forwards=20
from the Commodity Exchange Act does not affect the section=20
1256 tax analysis.
    Guidance under section 1256 is on the 2010-2011 Priority=20
Guidance Plan published by the Treasury Department and the IRS.=20
That guidance will address issues related to the Dodd-Frank=20
Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act amendment to=20
section 1256, including the scope of section 1256(b)(2). The=20
section 1256 guidance project is expected to be published this=20
summer.
