        RESPONSES TO WRITTEN QUESTIONS OF SENATOR HAGAN
                      FROM MARY J. MILLER

Q.1. On April 12, the banking regulators released their=20
proposal on ``Margin and Capital Requirements for Covered Swap=20
Entities.'' The proposal requires dealer banks and significant=20
counterparties to post two way initial margin and to hold that=20
margin at third party custodian banks. This margin would be=20
limited to immediately available cash funds and high-quality,=20
highly liquid U.S. Government and agency obligations. Re-
hypothecation of such amounts would be prohibited. What are the=20
costs associated with tying up margin in segregated accounts at=20
custodian banks? Have you quantified the impact this=20
requirement will have on liquidity?

A.1. As you note, the banking regulators released a notice of=20
proposed rulemaking on ``Margin and Capital Requirements for=20
Covered Swap Entities'' on April 12. Those proposed rules are=20
currently open for public comment. Among the questions on which=20
the banking regulators have solicited comments is what costs=20
the proposed rules would impose and what impact they would have=20
on liquidity. Comments are due by June 24, 2011. These are=20
clearly important questions, and we look forward to reviewing=20
the comments the banking regulators receive in response to=20
these and the many other questions they have asked.

Q.2. The margin and capital requirements proposal takes a risk-
based approach by distinguishing between four separate types of=20
derivatives counterparties. The proposal extends the definition=20
of financial end user to include any government of any foreign=20
country or any political subdivision, agency, or=20
instrumentality thereof in the world. How would margin and=20
capital requirements apply to the dealings of the foreign=20
subsidiary of a U.S. financial institution that enters into a=20
swap? What about a U.S. financial institution that enters into=20
a swap with a foreign government? Would the foreign subsidiary=20
of a U.S. institution that enters into a swap with a foreign=20
government be required to post margin in U.S. Treasuries?

A.2. As noted in response to the prior question, the banking=20
regulators released a notice of proposed rulemaking on ``Margin=20
and Capital Requirements for Covered Swap Entities'' on April=20
12 and have requested comments from the public by June 24,=20
2011. The proposed rules also have specifically solicited=20
comment on whether the proposed rules appropriately limit the=20
margin rules consistent with the territorial scope of the Dodd-
Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and how=20
the rules could affect the structure, management, and=20
competitiveness of U.S. entities.
